Complex vertebral malformation, bovine - Denmark: RFI 20010104.0030
[1
Date: 5 Jan 2001 15:35:09 +0100
From: Jorgen Agerholm <jager@kvl.dk>
Subject: Complex Vertebral Malformation, bovine

We recently recognized complex vertebral malformation (CVM) as a familial
occurring abnormality in Holstein calves. More than 30 cases have been
necropsied and about 100 reported by breeders during the last year. The
cases occur with only one or a few within each herd and, until now, in a
strict familial pattern in which both the sire and dam are genetically
related to the US Holstein bull "Bell."
We have performed a breeding trial with about 300 cows. If the disease was
inherited autosomal recessively about 30 malformed calves would have been
expected. We only got about 15. The causes of this are at present unknown,
but are currently under investigation. Calves may have been lost due to
abortion, or the rate of embryonic deaths may have increased. The cows were
selected based on a positive pregnancy diagnosis on day 52. The chromosomal
region in which the CVM gene is located has been identified. The region is
present on both chromosomes in affected calves and on one chromosome in the
parents.
Affected calves have been examined for bovine virus diarrhea virus (BVDV)
and antibodies against BVDV and _Neospora caninum_, in most cases with
negative results. Cases have been examined by necropsy, histopathology and
radiology without any evidence of an infectious etiology.
The skepticism from my point of view is based on 3 points:
1. The Danish breeding associations acted on the likely inheritance of CVM
very early, so the knowledge of CVM was distributed internationally before
we could finish our studies. Therefore, we couldn't provide published
scientific evidence.
2. Details regarding the genetic marker test were not made available due to
a patent application.
3. Cases have not been recorded in the US despite widespread use of sires
related to Bell. However, at least one case has now been diagnosed.
Further information can be obtained from
--
Jorgen Agerholm
J.S. Agerholm, Asst. Prof., DVM, PhD
Laboratory of Veterinary Pathology
The Royal Veterinary and Agricultural University
