Date: 5 Jan 2001 15:12:52 -0000
From: Helena Spedding <Helena.Spedding@pjbpubs.com>
Subject: Complex vertebral malformation, bovine - Denmark: RFI

I'm sure you were hoping for rather more than this but, just in case no one
else has sent you anything, I have these rather thin pickings to contribute
to the complex vertebral malformation thread. It certainly doesn't look
like an infectious disease from this stuff. CVM is also called the
Nixon-Defect at least in Denmark -- named after KOL Nixon.
Denmark has developed a DNA test for CVM and is the only county performing
it. It was developed by researchers from Foulum and the Danish agricultural
school. They hope to patent it. After each positive DNA test the owner is
informed and a week later the test result is published on
<http://www.lr.dk>. The bulls will no longer be used for stud.
This is only in Denmark and the other Nordic countries. In other countries
it is up to the farmer what to do, if and when he is informed of the test
result. <http://www.naab-css.org/education/CVMNAAB.html>
Go here:
<http://www.lr.dk/lr/system/kategorier/html/index.asp?menu=/cn=lr&expand=yes>
select s√∏gside and enter cvm you get loads of lists of test results
<http://www.lr.dk/kvaeg/diverse/avlsvaerdital.htm?expand=>
Articles in English:
<http://www.theagzone.com/zones/dairy/dl001115a.htm>
<http://www.cattle.dk/Raceforeninger/diverse/holstein/cvm.htm>
