[Ask & you shall receive. We are very grateful to Jorgen and Helena for
their excellent brief reports. As Jorgen says, it is strange that if CVM is
a genetic fault that to date there has been only one US report on this
condition, which seemingly is closely related to a US Holstein bull.
However, congenital problems have a bad habit of being hidden from public
view. Trust the Danes to make their reports publicly available. Here such a
public-spirited action would keep lawyers employed. I am surprised that
pregnancy was determined at Day +52; I would have gone for Day +36, but I
am not a theriogenologist. The difference, 15 calves vs 30 expected, might
be explained by early fetal death, as he notes. We will cut the thread at
this point and leave CVM to Jorgen & Helena to keep us informed if any
evidence emerges on an infectious component. - Mod.MHJ
